File: platform/browser-extension/src/tab-state.ts, lines 27-42

The pluginLocks Map stores per-plugin serialization promises. withPluginLock chains each new operation onto the previous promise via .then(). The chain grows linearly — each new promise holds a reference to the prior one, preventing GC of fulfilled promises.

Current code (simplified):
```
const prev = pluginLocks.get(name) ?? Promise.resolve();
const next = prev.then(fn).catch(() => {});
pluginLocks.set(name, next);
```

Fix: After the operation completes (in the .then callback), check if the lock still points to `next`. If so, reset it to Promise.resolve() to break the chain. This is safe because any concurrent withPluginLock call will have already chained onto `next`, creating a new promise that becomes the lock. The key insight: we only reset if no new work has been enqueued.

Example fix pattern:
```
const next = prev.then(fn).catch(() => {}).then(() => {
  if (pluginLocks.get(name) === next) {
    pluginLocks.set(name, Promise.resolve());
  }
});
pluginLocks.set(name, next);
```

Note: The .catch(() => {}) must come BEFORE the chain-breaking .then() so errors don't propagate.
